OPENDMARC REPORTS
=================

This directory contains tools necessary to generate DMARC reports at regular
intervals.  It includes the following:

	opendmarc-expire	perl script to expire old DMARC records from
				the database; meant to be run from cron

	opendmarc-expire.8	man page for the above

	opendmarc-import	perl script to import opendmarc history files
				into the database; meant to be run from cron

	opendmarc-import.8	man page for the above

	opendmarc-importstats	shell script to atomically rename the history
				file and feed it to opendmarc-import; useful
				as a cron wrapper around opendmarc-import when
				the filter writes a single shared history file

	opendmarc-importstats.8	man page for the above

	opendmarc-params	perl script to adjust domain-specific opendmarc
				data in the database

	opendmarc-params.8	man page for the above

	opendmarc-reports	perl script to generate DMARC aggregate (and
				optionally forensic) reports; meant to be run
				from cron

	opendmarc-reports.8	man page for the above

The adjacent "db" directory contains an SQL schema to be used with this
package.  The opendmarc filter populates the tables in that schema as messages
are received and DMARC policies evaluated.  The scripts in here use the
accumulated information to generate reports, and age out old data.

To use schema.mysql, enter the MySQL command line tool, connect to the
database in which you want to create the required tables, and type
"source schema.mysql".

DEPENDENCIES
============

The OpenDMARC reports package requires Perl >= 5.10 and the following modules:

  Required:
	DBD::mysql (or DBD::MariaDB)	DBI
	Date::Format			Getopt::Long
	IO::Compress::Gzip		JSON
	MIME::Base64			Net::DNS
	Net::SMTP			POSIX
	Sys::Syslog

  For HTTPS/HTTP report submission (rua= URIs with https:// or http://):
	LWP::UserAgent			URI

  For SMTP TLS (--smtp-ssl):
	IO::Socket::SSL

  For SMTP authentication (--smtp-username / --smtp-password):
	Net::SMTP (with Authen::SASL for AUTH support)

On Debian/Ubuntu:

	sudo apt-get install libdbi-perl libdbd-mysql-perl libdate-manip-perl \
	    libjson-perl libio-compress-perl libnet-dns-perl libwww-perl \
	    libauthen-sasl-perl

On Red Hat/Fedora/EPEL:

	sudo dnf install perl-DBI perl-DBD-MySQL perl-TimeDate perl-JSON \
	    perl-IO-Compress perl-Net-DNS perl-libwww-perl perl-Authen-SASL

SETUP
=====

1) From within the MySQL command line environment, "source schema.mysql" to
   create the required database and tables.  You may also wish to set up
   users and access grants for users that will access this data.

2) Add a HistoryFile entry to opendmarc.conf referring to the location where
   per-message DMARC details should be recorded.  This location should be
   readable and writable by the user running the filter, but nobody else.

3) Add a cron job to import the history file at regular intervals (each minute
   or at least every five minutes):

	* * * * *  opendmarc  opendmarc-importstats

   opendmarc-importstats atomically renames the history file and feeds the
   renamed copy to opendmarc-import.  The renamed file is removed after
   successful import.  Configure the history file path by editing the
   statsdb variable at the top of the script.

   Alternatively, call opendmarc-import directly if you manage the history
   file rotation yourself.

4) Add a cron job to expire old database records.  Running daily is typical:

	0 0 * * *  opendmarc  opendmarc-expire [options]

   See opendmarc-expire.8 for available options, including --days (default 90).

5) Add a cron job to generate and send aggregate reports.  Daily is typical:

	0 1 * * *  opendmarc  opendmarc-reports [options]

   See opendmarc-reports.8 for the full option list.  Commonly used options
   include:

	--dbhost	database host (also: OPENDMARC_DBHOST env variable)
	--dbname	database name (also: OPENDMARC_DB)
	--dbpasswd	database password (also: OPENDMARC_PASSWORD)
	--dbport	database port (also: OPENDMARC_PORT)
	--dbuser	database user (also: OPENDMARC_USER)
	--smtp-server	outbound MTA hostname
	--smtp-ssl	use TLS for outbound SMTP
	--smtp-username	SMTP AUTH username
	--smtp-password	SMTP AUTH password
	--report-email	envelope sender / From address for reports
	--report-org	organization name in reports
	--report-bcc	BCC all outgoing reports to this address
	--forensic	also generate per-message failure reports
	--verp		use VERP envelope senders for bounce tracking
	--config	path to a config file (avoids long cron command lines)

   opendmarc-reports also supports https:// and http:// URIs in rua= tags
   for report submission via HTTP POST per RFC 7489 §7.1.

   A contrib/opendmarc-run wrapper script is available for environment-variable-
   based configuration suitable for use in cron or a systemd timer.

